{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586631"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:36:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:36:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15083"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15083"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.5,0,0.33,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67900"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7771"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53365"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"12756"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18971"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67900"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic kidney disease is a significant health burden in Australia, particularly affecting Indigenous populations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about chronic kidney disease epidemiology in Australia is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1 in 1400 people receive kidney replacement therapy","Chronic glomerulonephritis is the leading cause of end-stage kidney disease","The prevalence is equal between Indigenous and non-Indigenous populations","3% of adults have chronic kidney disease","Polycystic kidney disease accounts for 25% of cases"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003E1 in 1400 people receive kidney replacement therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. This reflects the significant burden of end-stage kidney disease requiring dialysis or transplantation in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic glomerulonephritis is the leading cause\u003C/strong\u003E - Diabetic nephropathy is actually the leading cause of end-stage kidney disease in Australia, accounting for about 38% of new cases\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe prevalence is equal between Indigenous and non-Indigenous populations\u003C/strong\u003E - Indigenous Australians have much higher rates, being 3.7 times more likely to have chronic kidney disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E3% of adults have chronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E - The actual prevalence is about 10% of Australian adults\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic kidney disease accounts for 25% of cases\u003C/strong\u003E - This inherited condition accounts for a much smaller proportion of cases\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic kidney disease affects about 1.7 million Australian adults, with Indigenous Australians experiencing much higher rates of disease and earlier onset of end-stage kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic kidney disease affects approximately 1.7 million Australian adults, with significantly higher rates in Indigenous populations.","Approximately 1 in 1400 Australians receive kidney replacement therapy (dialysis or transplant).","Diabetic nephropathy is the leading cause of end-stage kidney disease in Australia, followed by hypertensive/vascular disease."],"references":["Jun M, Wick J, Neuen BL, Kotwal S, Badve SV, Woodward M, Chalmers J, Peiris D, Rodgers A, Nallaiah K, Jardine MJ, Perkovic V, Gallagher M, Ronksley PE. The Prevalence of CKD in Australian Primary Care: Analysis of a National General Practice Dataset. Kidney Int Rep. 2023 Nov 29;9(2):312-322. doi: 10.1016/j.ekir.2023.11.022. PMID: 38344725; PMCID: PMC10851013.","Radford J, Kitsos A, Stankovich J, Castelino R, Khanam M, Jose M, Peterson G, Saunder T, Wimmer B, Razizaidi T. Epidemiology of chronic kidney disease in Australian general practice: National Prescribing Service MedicineWise MedicineInsight dataset. Nephrology (Carlton). 2019 Oct;24(10):1017-1025. doi: 10.1111/nep.13537. Epub 2018 Dec 13. PMID: 30467996; PMCID: PMC6790712.","Hoy WE, Mott SA, McDonald SP. An update on chronic kidney disease in Aboriginal Australians. Clin Nephrol. 2020 Supplement-Jan;93(1):124-128. doi: 10.5414/CNP92S122. PMID: 31426912.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53365"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15083"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53365"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:24:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:26:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7771"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67900"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"